<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
[image]www.boortz.com/cryingeaglesm.jpg[/image]<br>
<br>
<br>
A year ago a group of brainwashed zealots stabbed at us out of instilled hatred, envy, and ignorance. Their act of utter barbarism caused us the pain of disbelief, loss, shock, anguish, economic strife, and absolue horror. But it also had the effect of bringing out the true American spirit -- something that is rarely seen, but a terrible, indomitable force to behold once unleashed.<br>
<br>
Stop and reflect for a moment on those who were lost. Mourn them but don't lose sight of the phoenix that arose literally out of the ashes. Don't focus on the sensationalism of the horrific imagery that is again splashed across our media. Instead, reflect on the civil servants who dedicate their lives to stopping those who would destroy our way of life, even at the peril of their own, and who come to our aid when we are in our greatest need. Stop and realize that, just as Adolf Hitler did in Nazi Germany six decades ago, there are people in places in this world who use Hate as a tool to gain power over the masses by focusing mob mentality on a perceived "enemy." And realize that many people have died to ensure that America does not ever become such a place.<br>
<br>
Nearly three thousand people died on the 11th of September, 2001 in the Twin Towers, but their deaths were not in vain. The unnecessary loss of life was tragic on an epic scale, it shattered an illusion of innocence but it served also to rekindle the spirit that so many others have sacrificed everything for in the past. A spirit which knows no equal in recorded history -- the spirit of American freedom.<br>
<br>
Stop for a moment and give a quiet word of thanks to all who have built the freedom you now enjoy, and those who strive to stand between you and adversity every day -- the police and firefighters, rescue workers and paramedics, people in the medical field and in the military, as well as many many countless others. These are often dangerous and yet thankless jobs. So change this -- tell them "thanks" once in a while.<br>
<br>
I pray that this note finds you all safe and that we never have to endure such a needless act of violence again in order to be reminded of who we really are, where we come from, or those who have come before us.<br>
